  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, **money laundering** falls under **criminal legislation** in most jurisdictions worldwide. It is considered a serious financial crime and is subject to stringent legal penalties.\n\n### Key Points:\n\n1. **Definition**: Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process makes the funds appear \"clean\" or legitimate.\n\n2. **Criminalization**: Money laundering is a crime under national and international laws. For example:\n   - In the **United States**, it is punishable under the **Money Laundering Control Act (1986)**.\n   - In the **European Union**, it is addressed under the **Anti-Money Laundering Directives (AMLD)**.\n   - Globally, the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)** sets international standards for combating money laundering.\n\n3. **Penalties**: Convictions for money laundering can result in severe consequences, including:\n   - Imprisonment\n   - Heavy fines\n   - Asset forfeiture\n   - Damage to reputation for businesses or individuals involved.\n\n4. **Associated Crimes**: Money laundering is often linked to other criminal activities, such as:\n   - Drug trafficking\n   - Fraud\n   - Terrorism financing\n   - Corruption\n\n5. **Prevention and Enforcement**: Governments and financial institutions have established measures to detect and prevent money laundering, such as **Know Your Customer (KYC)** regulations, transaction monitoring, and mandatory reporting of suspicious activities.\n\nIn summary, money laundering is a criminal offense under both domestic and international law, and those involved face significant legal repercussions.",
